{
  "text": "ATP production was determined using a bioluminescence technique [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Mitochondrial suspensions diluted in ATP-monitoring reagent (AMR, formula SL; BioThema AB, Dalar\u00f6, Finland; reconstituted according to supplier's recommendation in 1.2\u03eb concentration of buffer B) were added to cuvettes containing AMR, substrate, and ADP. Substrates added (in mM final concentration) were either 1) 1 pyruvate \u03e9 1 malate or 2) 1 pyruvate \u03e9 0.05 palmitoyl-L-carnitine \u03e9 1 malate \u03e9 10 \u2423-ketoglutarate, with additional blank tubes used for measuring background. For each animal, all ATP production reactions for the four tissue preparations were analyzed in duplicate simultaneously. ATP production was monitored at 25\u00b0C with an automated routine in a BioOrbit 1251 luminometer (BioOrbit Oy, Turku, Finland). Internal calibration of each reaction cuvette was achieved by the addition of an ATP standard. The time required to prepare the mitochondrial suspensions (\u03f390 min) and perform the ATP production assay (35 min) was standard for all animals studied. The variation between duplicate measurements of ATP production from a given preparation was consistently \u03fd6%. The reproducibility of the method was established before the study by dividing rat muscles or livers into 4-5 pieces and performing separate parallel analyses. The coefficients of variation for these preparations (9% for liver, 11% for muscle) were similar to those reported for human muscle studies [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
